{"id":"astro-ph/0410586","submitter":"Petri K\\\"apyl\\\"a","authors":"P. J. K\\\"apyl\\\"a (Oulu & KIS), M. J. Korpi (Helsinki), M. Ossendrijver\n  (KIS) & I. Tuominen (Helsinki)","title":"Local models of stellar convection III: The Strouhal number","comments":"7 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"A&A (2006), 448, 433-438","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361:20042245","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Aims: The Strouhal number (St), which is a nondimensional measure of the\ncorrelation time, is determined from numerical models of convection. The\nStrouhal number arises in the mean-field theories of angular momentum transport\nand magnetic field generation, where its value determines the validity of\ncertain widely used approximations, such as the first order smoothing\n(hereafter FOSA). More specifically, the relevant transport coefficients can be\ncalculated by means of a cumulative series expansion if St < St_crit \\approx 1.\nMethods: We define the Strouhal number as the ratio of the correlation and\nturnover times, which we determine separately, the former from the\nautocorrelation of velocity, and the latter by following test particles\nembedded in the flow. Results: We find that the Strouhal numbers are,\ngenerally, of the order of 0.1 to 0.4 which is close to the critical value\nabove which deviations from FOSA become significant. Increasing the rotational\ninfluence tends to shorten both timescales in such a manner that St decreases.\nHowever, we do not find a clear trend as function of the Rayleigh number for\nthe parameter range explored in the present study.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Oct 2004 10:03:06 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 15 Nov 2005 16:07:23 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 10 May 2006 12:50:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0410587","submitter":"Petri K\\\"apyl\\\"a","authors":"P. J. K\\\"apyl\\\"a (Oulu & KIS), M. J. Korpi (Nordita), M. Ossendrijver\n  (KIS) & I. Tuominen (Oulu & Helsinki)","title":"Estimates of the Strouhal number from numerical models of convection","comments":"4 pages, 2 figures. To appear in a special volume of Astronomische\n  Nachrichten for the conference 'Dynamos of the Sun, Stars & Planets', held in\n  Freiburg, Oct 4th-6th, 2004","journal-ref":"Astron.Nachr.326:186-189,2005","doi":"10.1002/asna.200410374","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We determine the Strouhal number (hereafter St), which is essentially a\nnondimensional measure of the correlation time, from numerical calculations of\nconvection. We use two independent methods to estimate St. Firstly, we apply\nthe minimal tau-approximation (MTA) on the equation of the time derivative of\nthe Reynolds stress. A relaxation time is obtained from which St can be\nestimated by normalising with a typical turnover time. Secondly, we calculate\nthe correlation and turnover times separately, the former from the\nautocorrelation of velocity and the latter by following test particles embedded\nin the flow. We find that the Strouhal number is in general of the order of 0.1\nto 1, i.e. rather large in comparison to the typical assumption in the\nmean-field theories that St << 1. However, there is a clear decreasing trend as\nfunction of the Rayleigh number and increasing rotation. Furthermore, for the\npresent range of parameters the decrease of St does not show signs of\nsaturation, indicating that in stellar convection zones, where the Rayleigh\nnumbers are much larger, the Strouhal number may indeed be significantly\nsmaller.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Oct 2004 10:22:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
